  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">Amos Farnsworth encloses three articles that were recently published in the Courier and relate to the Constitution, which he wishes Anne Warren Weston &quot;thoughtfully to read.&quot; Farnsworth states: &quot;It is perfect nonsense to talk of destroying the Constitution as an antislavery measure. It is a proslavery measure decidedly.&quot; Farnsworth&apos;s object is to get rid of slavery. He says: &quot;The American &amp; Mass. A. S. S. have given up the &apos;stuff of accomplishment&apos; &amp; everybody sees it to be so. The enemies of Garrison, of Old Org. of the A. S. cause are delighted with your present position; ...&quot; Furthermore, &quot;non resistance has placed the society in a somewhat ridiculous situation.&quot; He points out certain inconsistencies in the Society&apos;s position. Farnsworth believes that &quot;these ultraisms&quot; prevent accessions to the ranks of Old Organization. Farnsworth says: &quot;I am very sure that in 1845 in democratic U. States, power, aye, moral power, is very nearly in proportion to numbers.&quot;</subfield>
